Testing #6693

Modified `$\extensions\typescript\package.json`, added to the `grammars` section:

```
{
    "injectTo": ["source.ts"],
    "scopeName": "text.todo",
    "path": "./syntaxes/todo.json"
}
```

Added `$\extensions\typescript\syntaxes\todo.json`:

```
{
    "fileTypes": [],
    "injectionSelector": "comment, text.plain",
    "name": "TODO",
    "patterns": [
        {
            "match": "\\b(TODO|FIXME|CHANGED)\\b",
            "name": "storage.type.class.${1:/downcase}"
        },
        {
            "captures": {
                "1": {
                    "name": "markup.underline.link.radar"
                }
            },
            "match": "<(ra?dar:/(?:/problem|)/(?:[&0-9]+))>",
            "name": "storage.type.class.radar"
        }
    ],
    "scopeName": "text.todo"
}
```

I don't see it being picked up in TypeScript comments (inspecting the tokens also did not show it being picked up):
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5047891/15531100/b4f2008c-2258-11e6-96ad-b022373b1738.png)

- VSCode Version: 1.1.1
- OS Version: Windows 10 Pro

In Visual Studio (full version), I tend to turn off the Ctrl+LeftMouseClick go to definition feature. I personally prefer to have Ctrl+LeftMouseClick select the entire word under my mouse cursor.

From what I can see, mouse events are not configurable at the moment, and they are also not possible to override with extensions (to the best of my knowledge). It would be really nice to have a mouse mapping configuration file. Sublime Text has this (although it is sort of a hidden feature that is not exposed through the UI). Just as an example, my sublime text mousemap file looks like this:

``` json
[
    {
        "button": "button1", "count": 1, "modifiers": ["ctrl"],
        "press_command": "drag_select",
        "press_args": {"by": "words"}
    }
]
```
